---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SEOHead from '../../../components/SEOHead.astro';
---
<BaseLayout>
  <SEOHead
    slot="head"
    title="10 Best Okinawa Beaches — A Local's Honest Ranking"
    description="Forget the tourist rankings. A couple who's lived in Okinawa for 5 years ranks the beaches they actually visit on weekends."
    isArticle={true}
    publishedAt="2026-03-06"
  />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="ja" href="https://okinawa-go.jp/articles/okinawa-beach-ranking/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en" href="https://okinawa-go.jp/en/articles/okinawa-beach-ranking/" slot="head" />

  <article class="px-5 md:px-10 pt-24 md:pt-32 pb-20 md:pb-28 max-w-[680px] mx-auto">
    <header class="mb-12">
      <span class="label-text block mb-4">Activity</span>
      <h1 class="text-[28px] md:text-[40px] font-medium leading-[1.25] tracking-[-0.03em] text-[var(--text)] mb-4">
        10 Best Okinawa Beaches — A Local's Honest Ranking
      </h1>
      <p class="text-[13px] text-[var(--text-muted)]">March 6, 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="article-body text-[15px] leading-[2] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
      <p>
        Search "Okinawa beach ranking" online and Emerald Beach next to Churaumi Aquarium will top the list every time. As a resident, let me be blunt: those rankings measure fame and convenience, not actual beach quality.
      </p>
      <p>
        My wife and I have spent five years visiting beaches nearly every weekend. Our ranking criteria: water clarity, comfort, and "would we go back" factor.
      </p>

      <figure class="my-10">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507525428034-b723cf961d3e?w=800&q=80" alt="Crystal clear Okinawa ocean" class="w-full rounded" />
        <figcaption class="text-[11px] text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-3">Okinawa's water clarity is world-class</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#1: Sesoko Beach (Motobu)</h2>
      <p>
        Our undisputed number one on the main island. The water transparency is absurd — you can count grains of sand at your feet. Tropical fish swim in the shallows without needing to go out deep. The rocky areas on both ends of the beach are great for casual snorkeling — you'll find coral and fish without any gear rental.
      </p>
      <p>
        Downside: 1,000 yen parking and summer crowds. But even factoring that in, it's still #1. My wife says: "The most beautiful water on the main island is Sesoko. End of discussion."
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#2: Nishi-hama (Aka Island)</h2>

      <figure class="my-10">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544551763-46a013bb70d5?w=800&q=80" alt="Kerama islands clear water" class="w-full rounded" />
        <figcaption class="text-[11px] text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-3">Nishi-hama's Kerama Blue is in a league of its own</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>
        This is our outer-island pick, and we couldn't leave it off. Aka Island in the Kerama chain, about 90 minutes by ferry from Naha's Tomari Port. Day trips are possible.
      </p>
      <p>
        "Kerama Blue" is not a marketing term — it's a real, almost supernatural shade of blue that makes every mainland beach look dull in comparison. The moment you step into the water, you involuntarily gasp. Sea turtle sighting rates are high here too.
      </p>
      <p>
        Round-trip ferry is about 5,000 yen. Worth every yen. Go at least once.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#3: Kouri Beach (Nakijin)</h2>
      <p>
        Right after you cross the stunning Kouri Bridge. The beach underneath the bridge is beautiful and easy to access. Pro tip: use the free parking lot at the bridge base instead of the paid lots near the beach entrance — they're a short walk apart.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#4: Araha Beach (Chatan)</h2>
      <p>
        If we're ranking water clarity alone, this doesn't crack the top five. But for "total beach experience," it's a powerhouse. Free parking, restrooms, showers, playground, convenience store nearby, and the best sunsets on the island. This is the beach locals use most. It's the definition of usability.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#5: Moon Beach (Onna)</h2>

      <figure class="my-10">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519046904884-53103b34b206?w=800&q=80" alt="Crescent-shaped cove beach" class="w-full rounded" />
        <figcaption class="text-[11px] text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-3">Moon Beach's crescent cove has a unique, sheltered charm</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>
        In front of Hotel Moon Beach, but open to non-guests too. The crescent-shaped cove means gentle waves and sheltered swimming. The sand is powder-fine — walking barefoot here is genuinely pleasant. It feels like a private resort beach that happens to be public.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#6: Mibaru Beach (Nanjo)</h2>
      <p>
        The best in the south. About 30 minutes from Naha by car. It's a natural, unmanaged beach with a wild, untouched feel. They have glass-bottom boats run by local ojii (grandpas) for about 1,500 yen — you can peer into the ocean through the hull. Charming and surprisingly good.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#7: Zanpa Beach (Yomitan)</h2>
      <p>
        Near Cape Zanpa, a managed beach with solid facilities. What stands out is the water clarity — Yomitan beaches consistently have excellent visibility. They also have BBQ facilities, so if a beach barbecue is on your list, this is the spot.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#8: Emerald Beach (Motobu)</h2>
      <p>
        Inside the Churaumi Aquarium grounds. Well-managed and safe. Water quality doesn't quite match the top-ranked beaches, but combining it with an aquarium visit is genuinely convenient. Free entry. Ideal for families with kids.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#9: Tropical Beach (Ginowan)</h2>
      <p>
        The most well-equipped beach in Okinawa. Changing rooms, showers, lockers, shops, BBQ areas — everything. The water is mid-tier, but the central location near Naha and the frequent events make it a practical choice.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">#10: Toyosaki Chura SUN Beach (Tomigusuku)</h2>
      <p>
        The closest beach to Naha Airport — about 15 minutes by car. An artificial beach, so the quality is honestly not high. But the sheer convenience of being able to hit a beach 15 minutes after landing (or before departing) is unmatched. Perfect for squeezing in one last swim on your final day.
      </p>

      <hr class="my-14 border-[var(--border)]" />

      <h2 class="text-[20px] md:text-[24px] font-medium text-[var(--text)] mt-14 mb-6">How Locals Actually Use Beaches</h2>
      <p>
        Here's what tourists get wrong: they drive to a famous beach, take photos for 30 minutes, and leave. That's not how Okinawans do it.
      </p>
      <p>
        We pick a beach, spread out a sheet, buy tempura from a nearby stand, swim, nap, swim again. Half a day, minimum. One beach. No rushing.
      </p>
      <p>
        The beach isn't a checkmark on your itinerary. It's the whole point of the day.
      </p>
      <p>
        After five years here, that's the lesson that took us the longest to learn — and it changed everything.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
